{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523955"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:00:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:00:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13943"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13943"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.07,0.16,0.04,0.71]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6573"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91194"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6573"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13943"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75019"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43454"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91194"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man is admitted to the orthopaedic ward following a tibial fracture sustained during a car accident. During assessment at the Emergency Department he underwent a complete primary and secondary survey and no other injuries resulting from the accident were detected. He underwent closed reduction and full leg cast earlier in the day. The patient has a medical history of an unprovoked deep vein thrombosis. His only regular medication is rivaroxaban. At 4 am the patient is reviewed because of increasing leg pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient appears distressed. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 145/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. The affected leg shows erythema and glossy skin over the shin. There is severe pain on passive dorsiflexion of the toes. The patient reports decreased sensation between his first and second toes. Peripheral pulses are palpable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Other than removing the cast which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase analgesia and reassess in two hours","Start heparin infusion","Order a venous duplex ultrasound","Elevate the leg and apply an ice pack","Urgent fasciotomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents a case of suspected compartment syndrome, a surgical emergency that requires immediate intervention. The most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent fasciotomy\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient exhibits several classic signs of compartment syndrome: increasing pain out of proportion to the injury, pain on passive stretch (in this case, dorsiflexion of the toes), sensory changes (decreased sensation between first and second toes), and skin changes (erythema and glossy appearance).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing analgesia and reassessing in two hours\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially dangerous. Compartment syndrome is a time-sensitive condition, and delaying treatment can lead to irreversible muscle and nerve damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevating the leg and applying ice packs\u003C/strong\u003E might provide temporary relief but is insufficient for treating compartment syndrome. While it is a reasonable step in the management of post-operative swelling, it does not address the underlying issue of increased compartment pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting a heparin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate in this case. While the patient has a history of deep vein thrombosis and is on rivaroxaban, the current presentation is not consistent with a thrombotic event. Moreover, anticoagulation could worsen the situation if surgical intervention is needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrdering a venous duplex ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful if deep vein thrombosis was suspected, but the clinical picture here is more consistent with compartment syndrome. This investigation would delay necessary treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that compartment syndrome is a clinical diagnosis. While compartment pressure measurements can be helpful, they should not delay treatment if the clinical suspicion is high. The patient\u0027s use of rivaroxaban increases the risk of bleeding into the compartment, potentially exacerbating the condition. Prompt recognition and urgent surgical consultation for fasciotomy are crucial to prevent long-term complications such as muscle necrosis, contractures, and potential limb loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute leg pain after a tibial fracture raises the possibility of compartment syndrome, especially in a patient on anticoagulant medication.","Signs of compartment syndrome include pain and tenderness over the involved compartment, erythematous and glossy skin, sensory loss on the dorsum of the foot between first and second toes, increasing pain on passive stretching of the muscle groups, and foot drop."],"references":["Garner MR, Taylor SA, Gausden E, Lyden JP. Compartment syndrome: diagnosis, management, and unique concerns in the twenty-first century. HSS J. 2014 Jul;10(2):143-52. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4071472/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75019"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13943"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75019"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-15T08:07:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-15T08:07:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6573"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91194"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"